# ============= ReadMe ==============
echo "x - extracting ReadMe (Text)"
sed 's/^X//' << 'SHAR_EOF' > ReadMe &&
XQuantreg -- Quantile Regression (Version 2.0)
X
XThis is a submission to compute regression quantiles and some related
Xrank statistics.  It is a revision of a prior submission to incorporate
Xsome recent develoopments in rank based inference which employ
Xregression quantile ideas.  The submission  consists of:
X
X	rq.r--A ratfor subroutine 
X
Xand several S functions:
X
X	rq--which directly calls rq.o
X	trq--which computes analogues of the trimmed mean for regression
X	trq.print--which prints ls.print style output for trq
X	qrq--which is called by trq
X	ranks--which computes a vector of rank statistics from rq() output
X	rrs.test--which computes tests of linear hypotheses
X	rq.omega--estimates a scale parameter for the covariance matrix
X	dn--computes bandwidth for sparsity estimate
X
XThese eight functions all reside in a file called rq.s which could be read 
Xby S with the source() command.  Help files for the S functions are also 
Xprovided in the directory doc and could be moved to the appropriate .Data/.Help 
Xdirectory.  
X
XThe files were packaged as a unix shar archive.  A Makefile generated by
Xthe S CHAPTER command has been included to automate this process.  It has
Xbeen tested on Sun hardware, but may need editing.  With luck you might
Xtry 
X		make install
X		make load
X		make clean
X
XIf this works smoothly then invoking Splus in this directory will
Xautomatically load the new rq function and you can proceed from there.
X
X      This software has been submitted to Statlib and may be freely
X      used and redistributed for non-commercial purposes.  No guarantees
X      are offered or implied.  Comments, bug reports, etc are welcome
X      and should be sent to roger@ysidro.econ.uiuc.edu or to
X 
X 				Roger Koenker
X 				Department of Economics
X 				University of Illinois
X 				Champaign, Illinois, 61820
X 
XAcknowledgements:  Thanks to all those who have contributed comments
Xon this software following its initial submission in 1991,  particularly
Xto Gib Bassett, Steve Portnoy, Jana Jureckova, and Cornelius Gutenbrunner.
XSpecial thanks  to Pin Ng (U. of Houston) for help in preparing the new 
Xversion.
