# ============= rq.d ==============
echo "x - extracting rq.d (Text)"
sed 's/^X//' << 'SHAR_EOF' > rq.d &&
X.BG
X.FN rq
X.TL
XQuantile Regression
X.DN
XPerform a quantile regression on a design matrix, x, of explanatory variables and a vector, y, of responses. 
X.CS
Xrq(x, y, tau=-1, alpha=.1, dual=F, int=T, tol=1e-4, ci = T, method="score",
Xinterpolate=T, tcrit=T, hs=T)
X.PP
X.RA
X.AG x
Xvector or matrix of explanatory variables.  If  a  matrix,
Xeach  column represents a variable and each row represents
Xan observation (or case).  This should not contain  column
Xof  1s unless the argument intercept is FALSE.  The number
Xof rows of x should equal the number of elements of  y,  and
Xthere  should  be fewer columns than rows.  
XIf x is missing, rq() computes the ordinary
Xsample quantile(s) of y.
X.AG y
Xresponse vector with as many observations as the number of rows of x. 
X.OA
X.AG tau
Xdesired quantile. If tau is missing or outside the range [0,1]
Xthen all the regression quantiles are computed and the corresponding primal and dual solutions are returned.
X.AG alpha
Xlevel of significance for the confidence intervals; default is set at 10%.
X.AG dual
Xreturn the dual solution if TRUE (default).
X.AG int
Xflag for intercept; if TRUE (default) an intercept term is included in the regression.
X.AG tol
Xtolerance parameter for rq computations.
X.AG ci
Xflag for confidence interval; if TRUE (default) the confidence intervals are 
Xreturned.
X.AG method
Xif method="score" (default), ci is computed using regression rank score inversion;
Xif method="sparsity", ci is computed using sparsity function.
X.AG interpolate
Xif TRUE (default), the smoothed confidence intervals are returned.
X.AG tcrit
Xif tcrit=T (default), a finite sample adjustment of the critical point is
Xperformed using Student's t quantile, else the standard Gaussian quantile is 
Xused.
X.AG hs
Xlogical flag to use Hall-Sheather's sparsity estimator (default); otherwise Bofinger's
Xversion is used.
X.RT If tau is in [0,1] the function returns:
X.RC coef
Xthe estimated parameters of the tau-th conditional quantile function.
X.RC resid
Xthe estimated residuals of the tau-th conditional quantile function.
X.RC dual
Xthe dual solution (if dual=T).
X.RC h
Xthe index of observations in the basis.
X.RC ci
Xconfidence intervals (if ci=T).
X.RT If tau isn't in [0,1] the function returns:
X.RC sol
Xa  (p+2) by m matrix whose first row contains the 'breakpoints'
Xtau_1,tau_2,...tau_m, of the quantile function, 
Xi.e. the values in [0,1] at which the
Xsolution changes, row two contains the corresponding quantiles
Xevaluated at the mean design point, i.e. the inner product of
Xxbar and b(tau_i), and the last p rows of the matrix give b(tau_i).
XThe solution b(tau_i) prevails from tau_i to tau_i+1.
X.RC dsol
Xthe matrix of dual solutions corresponding to the primal solutions in sol.
XThis is an n by m matrix whose ij-th entry is 1 if y_i > x_i b(tau_j), 
Xis 0 if y_i < x_i b(tau_j),  and is between 0 and 1 otherwise, i.e. if
Xthe residual is zero.  See Gutenbrunner and Jureckova(1991) for a
Xdetailed discussion of the statistical interpretation of dsol.
X.RC h
Xthe matrix of observations indices in the basis corresponding to sol or dsol.
X.EX
Xrq(stack.x,stack.loss,.5)  #the l1 estimate for the stackloss data
Xrq(stack.x,stack.loss,tau=.5,ci=T,method="score")  #same as above with 
X	#regression rank score inversion confidence interval
Xrq(stack.x,stack.loss,.25)  #the 1st quartile, 
X	#note that 8 of the 21 points lie exactly 
X	#on this plane in 4-space
Xrq(stack.x,stack.loss,-1)   #this gives all of the rq solutions
Xrq(y=rnorm(10),method="sparsity")	#ordinary sample quantiles
X.SH METHOD
XThe algorithm used is a modification of the Barrodale and Roberts
Xalgorithm for l1-regression, l1fit in S, and is described in detail
Xin Koenker and d"Orey(1987).
X.KW regression quantiles, robust estimation, L-estimators
X.SH REFERENCES
X[1] Koenker, R.W. and Bassett, G.W. (1978). Regression quantiles, Econometrica, 46, 33-50.
X
X[2] Koenker, R.W. and d'Orey (1987). Computing Regression Quantiles. Applied Statistics, 36, 383-393.
X
X[3] Gutenbrunner, C. Jureckova, J. (1991). 
XRegression quantile and regression rank score process in the 
Xlinear model and derived statistics, Annals of Statistics, 20, 305-330.
X
X[4] Koenker, R.W. and d'Orey (1994).  Remark on Alg. AS 229: Computing Dual
XRegression Quantiles and Regression Rank Scores, Applied Statistics, 43, 410-414.
X
X[5] Koenker, R.W. (1994). Confidence Intervals for Regression Quantiles, in
XP. Mandl and M. Huskova (eds.), Asymptotic Statistics, 349-359, Springer-Verlag,
XNew York.
X
X.SH SEE ALSO
Xtrq and qrq for further details and references.
X.PP
X.WR
SHAR_EOF
$TOUCH -am 0517200595 rq.d &&
chmod 0644 rq.d ||
echo "restore of rq.d failed"
set `wc -c rq.d`;Wc_c=$1
if test "$Wc_c" != "4520"; then
	echo original size 4520, current size $Wc_c
fi
# ============= rq.r ==============
echo "x - extracting rq.r (Text)"
sed 's/^X//' << 'SHAR_EOF' > rq.r &&
X#     this software has been submitted to statlib and may be freely
X#     used and redistributed for non-commercial purposes.  no guarantees
X#     are offered or implied.  comments, bug reports, etc are welcome
X#     and should be sent to roger@ysidro.econ.uiuc.edu or to
X#
X#				roger koenker
X#				department of economics
X#				university of illinois
X#				champaign, illinois, 61820
X#
X#
Xsubroutine rq(m,nn,m5,n2,n4,a,b,t,toler,ift,x,e,s,wa,wb,nsol,ndsol,sol,dsol,lsol,h,qn,cutoff,ci,tnmat,big,lci1)
X#
X#     number of observations
X#     number of parameters
X#     m+5
X#     n+2
X#     n+4
X#     a is the x matrix
X#     b is the y vector
X#     t, the desired quantile
X#     toler, smallest detectable |x-y|/x machine precision to the 2/3
X#     ift exit code:
X#		0-ok
X#		else dimensions inconsistent
X#     x the parameter estimate betahat
X#     e is the residual vector
X#     s is an integer work array
X#     wa is a real work array
X#     wb is another real work array
X#     nsol is an estimated (row) dimension of the primal solution array say 3*m; minimum value = 2
X#     ndsol is an estimated (row) dimension of the dual solution array say 3*m; minimum value = 2
X#     sol is the primal solution array
X#     dsol is the dual solution arry
X#     lsol is the actual dimension of the solution arrays
X#     h is the matrix of basic observations indices
X#     qn is the vector of residuals variances from the projection of each column of the x matrix on the remaining columns
X#     cutoff, the critical point for N(0,1)
X#     ci is the matrix of confident intervals
X#     tnmat is the matrix of the JGPK rank test statistics
X#     big, large positive finite floating-point number
X#     utilization:  if you just want a solution at a single quantile you
X#     needn't bother with sol, nsol, etc, if you want all the solutions
X#     then set theta to something <0 and sol and dsol will return all the
X#     estimated quantile solutions.
X#     the algorithm  is a slightly modified version of algorithm as 229
X#     described in koenker and d'orey, "computing regression quantiles,
X#     applied statistics, pp. 383-393.
X#
Xinteger i,j,k,kl,kount,kr,l,lsol,m,m1,m2,m3,m4,m5,ift
Xinteger n,n1,n2,nsol,ndsol,out,s(m),h(nn,nsol)
Xinteger nn,n4,idxcf
Xlogical stage,test,init,iend,lup
Xlogical lci1,lci2,skip
Xreal a1,aux,b1,big,d,dif,pivot,smax,t,t0,t1,tnt
Xreal min,max,toler,zero,half,one,two
Xreal b(m),sol(n2,nsol),a(m,nn),x(nn),wa(m5,n4),wb(m)
Xreal sum,e(m),dsol(m,ndsol)
Xreal qn(nn),cutoff,ci(4,nn),tnmat(4,nn),tnew,told,tn
Xdata zero/0.00/
Xdata half/0.50/
Xdata one/1.00/
Xdata two/2.00/
X#
X#  check dimension parameters
X#
Xn=nn
Xift = 0
Xwa(m+2,nn+1) = one
Xif (m5!=m+5)
X	ift = 3
Xif (n2!=n+2)
X	ift = 4
Xif (n4!=n+4)
X	ift = 5
Xif (m<=zero||n<=zero)
X	ift = 6
Xif (ift<=two) {
X#
X#  initialization
X#
X	iend = .true.
X	lci2 = .false.
X	lup = .true.
X	skip = .false.
X	idxcf = 0
X	tnew = zero
X	tn = zero
X	m1 = m+1
X	n1 = n+1
X	n3 = n+3
X	m2 = m+2
X	m3 = m+3
X	m4 = m+4
X	do j = 1,n{
X		x(j) = zero
X		}
X	do i = 1,m
X		e(i) = zero
X	if (t<zero||t>one) {
X		t0 = one/float(m)-toler
X		t1 = one-t0
X		t = t0
X		iend = .false.
X		lci1 = .false.
X		}
X	repeat { #0
X		do i = 1,m {
X			k = 1
X			do j = 1,nn
X				if (k<=nn){
X					if(j==idxcf)
X						skip = .true.
X					else
X						skip = .false.
X					if(!skip){
X						wa(i,k) = a(i,j)
X						k = k+1
X						}
X					}	
X			wa(i,n4) = n+i
X			wa(i,n2) = b(i)
X			if (idxcf != 0)
X				wa(i,n3) = tnew*a(i,idxcf)
X			else
X				wa(i,n3) = zero
X			wa(i,n1) = wa(i,n2)-wa(i,n3)
X			if (wa(i,n1)<zero)
X				do j = 1,n4
X					wa(i,j) = -wa(i,j)
X			}
X		do j = 1,n {
X			wa(m4,j) = j
X			wa(m2,j) = zero
X			wa(m3,j) = zero
X			do i = 1,m {
X				aux = sign(one,wa(m4,j))*wa(i,j)
X				wa(m2,j) = wa(m2,j)+aux*(one-sign(one,wa(i,n4)))
X				wa(m3,j) = wa(m3,j)+aux*sign(one,wa(i,n4))
X				}
X			wa(m3,j) = two*wa(m3,j)
X			}
X		dif = zero
X		init = .false.
X		if(!lci2){
X#compute the columns means
X			do k = 1,n {
X				wa(m5,k) = zero
X				do i = 1,m{
X					wa(m5,k) = wa(m5,k)+a(i,k)
X					}
X				wa(m5,k) = wa(m5,k)/float(m)
X				}
X			}
X		lsol = 1
X		kount = 0
X		repeat { #1
X#
X# compute new marginal costs
X#
X			do j = 1,n{
X				wa(m1,j) = wa(m2,j)+wa(m3,j)*t
X				}
X			if (!init) {
X#
X# stage 1
X#
X# determine the vector to enter the basis
X#
X				stage = .true.
X				kr = 1
X				kl = 1
X				go to 30
X				}
X			repeat { #2
X#
X# stage 2
X#
X				stage = .false.
X				repeat { #3
X#
X# determine the vector to enter the basis
X#
X					max = -big
X					do j = kr,n {
X						d = wa(m1,j)
X						if (d<zero) {
X							if (d>(-two))
X								next 1
X							d = -d-two
X							}
X						if (d>max) {
X							max = d
X							in = j
X							}
X						}
X					if (max<=toler)
X						break 2
X					if (wa(m1,in)<=zero) {
X						do i = 1,m4
X							wa(i,in) = -wa(i,in)
X						wa(m1,in) = wa(m1,in)-two
X						wa(m2,in) = wa(m2,in)-two
X						}
X					repeat { #4
X#
X# determine the vector to leave the basis
X#
X						k = 0
X						do i = kl,m {
X							d = wa(i,in)
X							if (d>toler) {
X								k = k+1
X								wb(k) = wa(i,n1)/d
X								s(k) = i
X								test = .true.
X								}
X							}
X						repeat { #5
X							if (k<=0)
X								test = .false.
X							else {
X								min = big
X								do i = 1,k
X									if (wb(i)<min) {
X										j = i
X										min = wb(i)
X										out = s(i)
X										}
X								wb(j) = wb(k)
X								s(j) = s(k)
X								k = k-1
X								}
X#
X# check for linear dependence in stage 1
X#
X							if (!test&&stage)
X								break 1
X							if (!test)
X								break 5
X							pivot = wa(out,in)
X							if (wa(m1,in)-pivot-pivot<=toler){
X								go to 10
X								}
X							do j = kr,n3 {
X								d = wa(out,j)
X								wa(m1,j) = wa(m1,j)-d-d
X								wa(m2,j) = wa(m2,j)-d-d
X								wa(out,j) = -d
X								}
X							wa(out,n4) = -wa(out,n4)
X							} #5
X						do i = 1,m4 {
X							d = wa(i,kr)
X							wa(i,kr) = wa(i,in)
X							wa(i,in) = d
X							}
X						kr = kr+1
X						go to 20
X#
X# pivot on wa(out,in)
X#
X						10  do j = kr,n3
X							if (j!=in)
X								wa(out,j) = wa(out,j)/pivot
X						do i = 1,m3
X							if (i!=out) {
X								d = wa(i,in)
X								do j = kr,n3
X									if (j!=in)
X										wa(i,j) = wa(i,j)-d*wa(out,j)
X								}
X						do i = 1,m3
X							if (i!=out)
X								wa(i,in) = -wa(i,in)/pivot
X						wa(out,in) = one/pivot
X						d = wa(out,n4)
X						wa(out,n4) = wa(m4,in)
X						wa(m4,in) = d
X						kount = kount+1
X						if (!stage)
X							break 1
X#
X# interchange rows in stage 1
X#
X						kl = kl+1
X						do j = kr,n4 {
X							d = wa(out,j)
X							wa(out,j) = wa(kount,j)
X							wa(kount,j) = d
X							}
X						20  if (kount+kr==n1)
X							break 2
X						30  max = -one
X						do j = kr,n
X							if (abs(wa(m4,j))<=n) {
X								d = abs(wa(m1,j))
X								if (d>max) {
X									max = d
X									in = j
X									}
X								}
X						if (wa(m1,in)<zero)
X							do i = 1,m4
X								wa(i,in) = -wa(i,in)
X						} #4
X					} #3
X				} #2
X			if (kr==1) {
X				do j = 1,n {
X					d = abs(wa(m1,j))
X					if (d<=toler||two-d<=toler){
X						ift = 1
X						wa(m2,nn+1) = zero
X						go to 80
X						}
X					}
X				}
X			80 kount = 0
X			sum = zero
X			if (!lci2){
X				do i = 1,kl-1 {
X					k = wa(i,n4)*sign(one,wa(i,n4))
X					x(k) = wa(i,n1)*sign(one,wa(i,n4))
X					}
X				}
X			do i = 1,n {
X				kd = abs(wa(m4,i))-n
X				dsol(kd,lsol) = one+wa(m1,i)/two
X				if (wa(m4,i)<zero)
X					dsol(kd,lsol) = one-dsol(kd,lsol)
X				if (!lci2){
X					sum = sum+x(i)*wa(m5,i)
X					sol(i+2,lsol) = x(i)
X					h(i,lsol) = kd
X					}
X				}
X			do i = kl,m {
X				kd = abs(wa(i,n4))-n
X				if (wa(i,n4)<zero)
X					dsol(kd,lsol) = zero
X				if (wa(i,n4)>zero)
X					dsol(kd,lsol) = one
X				}
X			if (!lci2){
X				sol(1,lsol) = smax
X				sol(2,lsol) = sum
X				do i=1,m
X					dsol(i,lsol+1) = dsol(i,lsol)
X				}
X			if (lci2){
X# compute next theta
X				a1 = zero
X				do i = 1,m {
X					a1 = a1+a(i,idxcf)*(dsol(i,lsol)+t-one)
X					}
X				tn = a1/sqrt(qn(idxcf)*t*(one-t))
X				if (abs(tn)<cutoff){
X					if (lup)
X						smax = big
X					else
X						smax = -big
X					do i =1,kl-1 {
X						k = wa(i,n4)*sign(one,wa(i,n4))
X						sol(k,1) = wa(i,n2)*sign(one,wa(i,n4))
X						sol(k,2) = wa(i,n3)*sign(one,wa(i,n4))/tnew
X						}
X					do i = kl,m {
X						a1 = zero
X						b1 = zero
X						k = wa(i,n4)*sign(one,wa(i,n4))-n
X						l = 1
X						do j = 1,n{
X							if (j==idxcf)
X								l = l+1
X							a1 = a1 + a(k,l)*sol(j,1)
X							b1 = b1 + a(k,l)*sol(j,2)
X							l = l+1
X							}
X						tnt = (b(k)-a1)/(a(k,idxcf)-b1)
X						if (lup){
X							if (tnt>tnew)
X								if (tnt<smax){
X									smax = tnt
X									out = i
X									}
X							}
X						else {
X							if (tnt<tnew)
X								if (tnt>smax){
X									smax = tnt
X									out = i
X									}
X							}
X						}
X					if (lup){
X						told = tnew 
X						tnew = smax + toler
X						ci(3,idxcf) = told - toler
X						tnmat(3,idxcf) = tn
X						if (!(tnew < big-toler)){
X							ci(3,idxcf) = big
X							ci(4,idxcf) = big
X							tnmat(3,idxcf) = tn
X							tnmat(4,idxcf) = tn
X							lup = .false.
X							go to 70
X							}
X						}
X					else{
X						told = tnew 
X						tnew = smax - toler
X						ci(2,idxcf) = told + toler
X						tnmat(2,idxcf) = tn
X						if (!(tnew > -big+toler)){
X							ci(2,idxcf) = -big
X							ci(1,idxcf) = -big
X							tnmat(2,idxcf) = tn
X							tnmat(1,idxcf) = tn
X							lup = .true.
X							go to 60
X							}
X						}
X#update the new marginal cost
X					do i = 1,m{
X						wa(i,n3) = wa(i,n3)/told*tnew
X						wa(i,n1) = wa(i,n2) - wa(i,n3)
X						}
X					do j = kr,n3{
X						d = wa(out,j)
X						wa(m1,j) = wa(m1,j) -d -d
X						wa(m2,j) = wa(m2,j) -d -d
X						wa(out,j) = -d
X						}
X					wa(out,n4) = -wa(out,n4)
X					init = .true.
X					}
X				else{
X					if (lup){
X						ci(4,idxcf) = tnew - toler
X						tnmat(4,idxcf) = tn
X						lup = .false.
X						go to 70
X						}
X					else{
X						ci(1,idxcf) = tnew + toler
X						tnmat(1,idxcf) = tn
X						lup = .true.
X						go to 60
X						}
X					}
X				}
X			if ((iend)&&(!lci2))
X				go to 40
X			if (!lci2){
X				init = .true.
X				lsol = lsol+1
X				do i = 1,m
X					s(i) = zero
X				do j = 1,n
X					x(j) = zero
X#
X#  compute next t
X#
X				smax = two
X				do j = 1,n {
X					b1 = wa(m3,j)
X					a1 = (-two-wa(m2,j))/b1
X					b1 = -wa(m2,j)/b1
X					if (a1>=t)
X						if (a1<smax) {
X							smax = a1
X							dif = (b1-a1)/two
X							}
X					if (b1>t)
X						if (b1<smax) {
X							smax = b1
X							dif = (b1-a1)/two
X							}
X					}
X				tnt = smax+toler*(one+abs(dif))
X				if (tnt>=t1+toler)
X					iend = .true.
X				t = tnt
X				if (iend)
X					t = t1
X				}
X			} #1
X		wa(m2,nn+1) = two
X		ift = 2
X		go to 50
X		40  if (lsol>2) {
X			sol(1,1) = zero
X			sol(1,lsol) = one
X			do i = 1,m {
X				dsol(i,1) = one
X				dsol(i,lsol) = zero
X				dsol(i,lsol+1) = zero
X				}
X			}
X		l = kl-1
X		do i = 1,l
X			if (wa(i,n1)<zero)
X				do j = kr,n4
X					wa(i,j) = -wa(i,j)
X		50  sum = zero
X		if(!lci2){
X			do i = kl,m {
X				k = wa(i,n4)*sign(one,wa(i,n4))
X				d = wa(i,n1)*sign(one,wa(i,n4))
X				sum = sum+d*sign(one,d)*(half+sign(one,d)*(t-half))
X				k = k-n
X				e(k) = d
X				}
X			wa(m2,n2) = kount
X			wa(m1,n2) = n1-kr
X			wa(m1,n1) = sum
X			}
X		if (wa(m2,nn+1)==two)
X			break 1
X		if (!lci1)
X			break 1
X		if (!lci2){
X			lci2 = .true.
X			n = nn-1
X			n1 = n+1
X			n2 = n+2
X			n3 = n+3
X			n4 = n+4
X		60	idxcf = idxcf+1
X			if (idxcf>nn)
X				break 1
X		70	if (lup){
X				tnew = x(idxcf)+toler
X				told = tnew
X				ci(3,idxcf) = x(idxcf)
X				tnmat(3,idxcf) = zero
X				}
X			else{
X				tnew = x(idxcf)-toler
X				told = tnew
X				ci(2,idxcf) = x(idxcf)
X				tnmat(2,idxcf) = zero
X				}
X			}
X		} #0
X	# restore the original value of dual when ci is true
X	do i=1,m
X		dsol(i,lsol) = dsol(i,lsol+1)
X	}
Xreturn
Xend
SHAR_EOF
$TOUCH -am 0517205995 rq.r &&
chmod 0644 rq.r ||
echo "restore of rq.r failed"
set `wc -c rq.r`;Wc_c=$1
if test "$Wc_c" != "11352"; then
	echo original size 11352, current size $Wc_c
fi
# ============= rq.s ==============
echo "x - extracting rq.s (Text)"
sed 's/^X//' << 'SHAR_EOF' > rq.s &&
X"qrq"<-
Xfunction(s, a)
X{
X#computes linearized quantiles from rq data structure
X#s is the rq structure e.g. rq(x,y)
X#a is a vector of quantiles required
X	if(min(a) < 0 || max(a) > 1) stop("alphas out of range [0,1]")
X	r <- s$sol[1,  ]
X	q <- s$sol[2,  ]
X	q <- c(q[1], q)
X	J <- length(r)
X	r <- c(0, (r[1:J - 1] + r[2:J])/2, 1)
X	u <- rep(0, length(a))
X	for(k in 1:length(a)) {
X		i <- sum(r < a[k])
X		w <- (a[k] - r[i])/(r[i + 1] - r[i])
X		u[k] <- w * q[i + 1] + (1 - w) * q[i]
X	}
X	u
X}
X"rq"<-
Xfunction(x, y, tau = -1, alpha = 0.10000000000000001, dual = F, int = T, tol
X	 = 0.0001, ci = T, method="score", interpolate = T, tcrit = T, hs=T)
X{
X#function to compute regression quantiles
X	if(!is.loaded(symbol.For("rq")))
X		dyn.load("rq_l.o")
X	if((tau<=0 || tau>=1) && ci){
X		warning("cannot compute confidence intervals for all tau")
X		ci <- F
X		}
X	if(ci && method != "score" && method != "sparsity"){
X		stop("method has to be ``score'' or ``sparsity''")
X		}
X	if(missing(x)) {
X		x <- matrix(rep(1, length(y)), length(y))
X		int <- FALSE
X		if(ci && method=="score"){
X			warning("method has been set to ``sparsity'' to compute confidence interval for sample quantile")
X			method <- "sparsity"
X			}
X		}
X	else{
X		x <- as.matrix(x)
X		if(int) 
X			x <- cbind(1, x)
X		else if(ncol(x)==1 && ci && method=="score"){
X			warning("method has been set to ``sparsity'' to compute confidence interval when x has only one column with no intercept")
X			method <- "sparsity"
X			}
X		}
X	big <- .Machine$single.xmax
X	x <- as.matrix(x)
X	p <- ncol(x)
X	n <- nrow(x)
X	if(n != length(y))
X		stop("x and y don't match n")
X	nsol <- 2
X	ndsol <- 2
X	if(tcrit)
X		cutoff <- qt(1 - alpha/2, n - p)
X        else 
X		cutoff <- qnorm(1 - alpha/2)
X	if(ci){
X		xxinv <- solve(crossprod(x))
X		qn <- 1/diag(xxinv)
X		}
X	else
X		qn <- rep(0,p)
X	t.orig <- tau
X	if(tau < 0 || tau > 1 || (ci && method=="sparsity")) {
X		nsol <- 3 * n
X		lci1 <- F
X		ndsol <- nsol
X		tau <- -1
X		}
X	else {
X		if(!ci)
X			lci1 <- F
X		else lci1 <- T
X		}
X	z <- .Fortran("rq",
X		as.integer(n),
X		as.integer(p),
X		as.integer(n + 5),
X		as.integer(p + 2),
X		as.integer(p + 4),
X		as.single(x),
X		as.single(y),
X		as.single(tau),
X		as.single(tol),
X		flag = as.integer(1),
X		coef = single(p),
X		resid = single(n),
X		integer(n),
X		single((n + 5) * (p + 4)),
X		single(n),
X		as.integer(nsol),
X		as.integer(ndsol),
X		sol = single((p + 2) * nsol),
X		dsol = single(n * ndsol),
X		lsol = as.integer(0),
X		h = integer(p * nsol),
X		qn = as.single(qn),
X		cutoff = as.single(cutoff),
X		ci = single(4 * p),
X		tnmat = single(4 * p),
X		as.single(big),
X		as.logical(lci1))
X	tau <- t.orig
X	if(z$flag != 0)
X		warning(switch(z$flag,"Solution may be nonunique",
X		"Premature end - possible conditioning problem in x."))
X	if(tau < 0 || tau > 1) {
X		z$sol <- matrix(z$sol, p + 2, z$lsol)
X		if(length(dimnames(x)[[2]]) == 0) {
X			if(int)
X				xn <- c("Intercept", paste("X", 1:(p - 1), sep
X				   = ""))
X			else xn <- paste("X", 1:p, sep = "")
X			}
X		else {
X			xn <- dimnames(x)[[2]]
X			if(int)
X				xn[1] <- "Intercept"
X			}
X		dimnames(z$sol) <- list(c("Probility", "Quantile", xn), NULL)
X		z$h <- matrix(z$h, p, z$lsol)
X		if(dual) {
X			z$dsol <- matrix(z$dsol, n, z$lsol)
X			z[c("sol", "dsol", "h")]
X			}
X		else z[c("sol", "h")]
X		}
X	else {
X		if(ci){
X			if(method=="score") {
X				if(interpolate){
X					Tn <- matrix(z$tnmat, nrow = 4)
X					Tci <- matrix(z$ci, nrow = 4)
X					Tci[3,] <- Tci[3,] + (cutoff - abs(Tn[3,
X					]))/abs(Tn[4,] - Tn[3,]) * abs(Tci[4,] - 					Tci[3,])
X					Tci[2,] <- Tci[2,] - (cutoff - abs(Tn[2,
X					]))/abs(Tn[1,] - Tn[2,]) * abs(Tci[1,] - 					Tci[2,])
X					Tci[2,  ][is.na(Tci[2,  ])] <-  - big
X					Tci[3,  ][is.na(Tci[3,  ])] <- big
X					dimnames(Tci)<-list(c("Lower Bound",
X					"Lower Bound","Upper Bound",
X					"Upper Bound"),NULL)
X					if(dual)
X						return(coef = z$coef, resid = 
X						z$resid, dual = z$dsol[1:n], 
X						h = z$h[1:p], ci = Tci[2:3,  ])
X					else 
X						return(coef = z$coef, resid = 
X						z$resid, h = z$h[1:p], ci = 
X						Tci[2:3,  ])
X					}
X				else {
X					Tci <- matrix(z$ci,nrow=4)
X					dimnames(Tci)<-list(c("Lower Bound",
X					"Lower Bound","Upper Bound",
X					"Upper Bound"),NULL)
X					if(dual)
X						return(coef = z$coef, resid = 
X						z$resid, dual = z$dsol[1:n], 
X						h = z$h[1:p], ci = Tci, Tn = 
X						matrix(z$tnmat, nrow = 4))
X					else return(coef = z$coef, resid = 
X						z$resid, h = z$h[1:p], ci = 
X						Tci, Tn = matrix(z$tnmat, 
X						nrow = 4))
X					}
X				}
X			else if(method=="sparsity"){
X				z$sol<-matrix(z$sol,p+2,z$lsol)
X				z$dsol<-matrix(z$dsol,n,z$lsol)
X				z$h <- matrix(z$h,p,z$lsol)
X				se<-diag(rq.omega(z,tau,hs=hs)*xxinv)^.5
X				Tci<-matrix(0,2,p)
X				dimnames(Tci)<-list(c("Lower Bound",
X				"Upper Bound"),NULL)
X				isol <- sum(z$sol[1,]<=tau)
X				Tcoef<-z$sol[3:(p+2),isol]
X				Tci[1,]<-Tcoef-cutoff*se
X				Tci[2,]<-Tcoef+cutoff*se
X				if(dual)
X					return(coef=Tcoef, resid=as.single(
X					y-x%*%Tcoef), dual = z$dsol[,isol], 
X					h = z$h[,isol], ci=Tci)
X				else 
X					return(coef=Tcoef, resid=as.single(
X					y-x%*%Tcoef), h = z$h[,isol], ci=Tci)
X				}
X			}
X		else {
X			if(dual)
X				return(coef = z$coef, resid = z$resid, dual = 
X				z$dsol[1:n], h = z$h[1:p])
X			else 
X				return(coef = z$coef, resid = z$resid, h = 
X				z$h[1:p])
X			}
X		}
X}
X"rq.omega"<-
Xfunction(z, tau = 0.5, hs = F, tol = 0.0001)
X{
X#computes omega^2=tau(1-tau)/f^2(xi_a) for se of rq's
X#uses linearized eqf from the full rq-process see function qrq()
X#bandwidth is either Bofinger (hs=F) or Hall-Sheather (hs=T)
X#z is the rq structure 
X	dn <- dn(tau, nrow(z$dsol), hs = hs)
X	low <- tau-dn
X	up <- tau+dn
X	if(low<0 || up>1){
X		warning("bandwidth is truncated to [0,1]")
X		low <- z$sol[1,2]
X		up <- z$sol[1,ncol(z$sol)-1]
X		}
X	q <- qrq(z, c(low, up))
X	shat <- diff(q)/(2 * dn)
X	tau * (1 - tau) * shat^2
X}
X"dn"<-
Xfunction(p, n, hs = F)
X{
X	PI <- 3.1415899999999999
X	x0 <- qnorm(p)
X	f0 <- (1/sqrt(2 * PI)) * exp(.Uminus((x0^2/2)))
X	if(hs == T)
X		n^(-1/3) * qnorm(1 - 0.025000000000000001)^(2/3) * ((1.5 * f0^2
X			)/(2 * x0^2 + 1))^(1/3)
X	else n^-0.20000000000000001 * ((4.5 * f0^4)/(2 * x0^2 + 1)^2)^
X			0.20000000000000001
X}
X"trq"<-
Xfunction(x, y, a1 = 0.1, a2, z, int = T, method = "primal", tol = 0.0001)
X{
X#compute trimmed regression quantiles
X#z is the rq strcture 
X	if(missing(a2)) a2 <- a1
X	if(a1 < 0 || a2 < 0)
X		stop("trimming proportion negative.")
X	if(a1 + a2 - 1 > tol)
X		stop("trimming proportion greater than 1.")
X	if(method!="primal" && method!="dual")
X		stop("invalid method: should be 'primal' or 'dual'.")
X	x <- as.matrix(x)
X	if(missing(z))
X		z <- rq(x, y,  , int, tol)
X	p <- z$sol[1,  ]
X	q <- matrix(z$sol[ - c(1, 2),  ], nrow(z$sol) - 2, ncol(z$sol))
X	n <- nrow(z$dsol)
X	s <- NULL
X	if(length(dimnames(x)[[2]]) == 0)
X		dimnames(x) <- list(NULL, paste("X", 1:(nrow(q) - 1), sep = "")
X			)
X	if(int) {
X		x <- cbind(1, x)
X		dimnames(x)[[2]][1] <- "Intercept"
X	}
X	xbar <- apply(x, 2, "mean")
X	xxinv <- solve(t(x) %*% x)
X	if(abs(a1 + a2 - 1) <= tol) {
X#single quantile case
X		i <- sum(p < a1)
X		s$coef <- q[, i]
X		names(s$coef) <- dimnames(x)[[2]]
X		s$resid <- y - x %*% s$coef
X		PI <- 3.14159
X		x0 <- qnorm(a1)
X		d0 <- (1/sqrt(2 * PI)) * exp( - (x0^2/2))
X		d0 <- ((4.5 * d0^4)/(2 * x0^2 + 1)^2)^0.2
X		d <- d0 * (length(s$resid) - length(s$coef))^(-0.2)
X		if(d > min(a1, 1 - a1))
X			d <- min(a1, 1 - a1)
X		s$d <- d
X		i <- sum(p < a1 + d)
X		j <- sum(p < a1 - d)
X		shat <- as.numeric(xbar %*% t(q[, i] - q[, j]))/(2 * d)
X		s$int <- int
X		s$v <- a1 * (1 - a1) * shat^2
X		s$cov <- s$v * xxinv
X	}
X	else {
X#real trimming
X		p1 <- p[-1]
X		f <- 1/(1 - a1 - a2)
X		d <- pmax((pmin(p1, 1 - a2) - c(a1, pmax(p1[ - length(p1)],
X			a1))), 0)
X		if(method == "primal") {
X			s$coef <- q[, 1:length(p1)] %*% t(d) * f
X			s$resid <- y - x %*% s$coef
X			s$int <- int
X		}
X		else {
X#Jureckova-Gutenbrunner trimmed least squares
X			i <- max(1, sum(p < a1))
X			g <- (z$dsol[, i + 1] - z$dsol[, i])/(p[i + 1] - p[
X				i])
X			wa <- z$dsol[, i] + (a1 - p[i]) * g
X			j <- sum(p < 1 - a2)
X			g <- (z$dsol[, j + 1] - z$dsol[, j])/(p[j + 1] - p[
X				j])
X			wb <- z$dsol[, j] + (1 - a2 - p[j]) * g
X			wt <- wa - wb
X			if(min(wt) < 0)
X				warning("some weights negative!")
X			s <- lsfit(x, y, abs(wt), int = F)
X		}
X#now compute covariance matrix estimate
X		mu <- xbar %*% s$coef
X		v <- d %*% t((z$sol[2, 1:length(d)] - mu)^2)
X		k <- qrq(z, c(a1, a2)) - mu
X		v <- v + a1 * k[1]^2 + a2 * k[2]^2 + (a1 * k[1] + a2 * k[2])^2
X		names(s$coef) <- dimnames(x)[[2]]
X		s$v <- as.vector(f^2 * v)
X		s$cov <- s$v * xxinv
X	}
X	s
X}
X"trq.print"<-
Xfunction(trq.out, digits = 4)
X{
X	n <- length(trq.out$resid)
X	p <- length(trq.out$coef)
X	options(warn = -1)
X	if(trq.out$int) {
X		df.num <- p - 1
X		fstat <- c(trq.out$coef[-1] %*% solve(trq.out$cov[-1, -1]) %*%
X			t(trq.out$coef[-1]))/df.num
X	}
X	else {
X		df.num <- p
X		fstat <- trq.out$coef %*% solve(trq.out$cov) %*% t(trq.out$coef
X			)/df.num
X	}
X	pvalue <- 1 - pf(fstat, df.num, (n - p))
X	cat(paste("Winsorized Standard Error of Regression= ", format(round(
X		sqrt(trq.out$v), digits)), "\n", "N = ", format(n), 
X		",  F-statistic = ", format(round(fstat, digits)), " on ",
X		format(df.num), " and ", format((n - p)), " df, ", "p-value = ",
X		format(round(pvalue, digits)), "\n\n", sep = ""))
X	regstat <- c(sqrt(trq.out$v), n, fstat, df.num, (n - p), pvalue)
X	names(regstat) <- c("rse", "n", "F.stat", "df.num", "df.den", "p.value"
X		)
X	err <- sqrt(diag(trq.out$cov))
X	tstat <- c(trq.out$coef/err)
X	tabcoef <- cbind(trq.out$coef, err, tstat, 2 * (1 - pt(abs(tstat),
X		n - p)))
X	dimnames(tabcoef) <- list(names(trq.out$coef), c("coef", "std.err",
X		"t.stat", "p.value"))
X	options(warn = 0)
X	print(round(tabcoef, digits))
X	invisible(list(summary = regstat, coef.table = tabcoef))
X}
X"ranks"<-
Xfunction(v, score = "wilcoxon")
X{
X	A2 <- 1
X	if(score == "wilcoxon") {
X		J <- ncol(v$sol)
X		dt <- v$sol[1, 2:J] - v$sol[1, 1:(J - 1)]
X		ranks <- as.vector((0.5 * (v$dsol[, 2:J] + v$dsol[, 1:(J - 1)]) %*%
X			dt) - 0.5)
X		return(ranks, A2 = 1/12)
X	}
X	else if(score == "normal") {
X		J <- ncol(v$sol)
X		dt <- v$sol[1, 2:J] - v$sol[1, 1:(J - 1)]
X		dphi <- c(0, phi(qnorm(v$sol[1, 2:(J - 1)])), 0)
X		dphi <- diff(dphi)
X		ranks <- as.vector((((v$dsol[, 2:J] - v$dsol[, 1:(J - 1)]))) %*% (
X			dphi/dt))
X		return(ranks, A2)
X	}
X	else if(score == "sign") {
X		j.5 <- sum(v$sol[1,  ] < 0.5)
X		w <- (0.5 - v$sol[1, j.5])/(v$sol[1, j.5 + 1] - v$sol[1, j.5])
X		r <- w * v$dsol[, j.5 + 1] + (1 - w) * v$dsol[, j.5]
X		return(ranks = 2 * r - 1, A2)
X	}
X	else stop("invalid score function")
X}
X"rrs.test"<-
Xfunction(x0, x1, y, v, score = "wilcoxon")
X{
X	if(missing(v) || is.null(v$dsol))
X		v <- rq(x0, y, dual = T)
X	r <- ranks(v, score)
X	x1hat <- as.matrix(qr.resid(qr(cbind(1, x0)), x1))
X	sn <- as.matrix(t(x1hat) %*% r$ranks)
X	sn <- t(sn) %*% solve(crossprod(x1hat)) %*% sn/r$A2
X	return(sn, rank = r$ranks)
X}
SHAR_EOF
$TOUCH -am 0517200595 rq.s &&
chmod 0644 rq.s ||
echo "restore of rq.s failed"
set `wc -c rq.s`;Wc_c=$1
if test "$Wc_c" != "10737"; then
	echo original size 10737, current size $Wc_c
fi
# ============= rrs.test.d ==============
echo "x - extracting rrs.test.d (Text)"
sed 's/^X//' << 'SHAR_EOF' > rrs.test.d &&
X.BG
X.FN rrs.test
X.TL
XFunction to compute regression rankscore test of linear hypothesis
X.DN
XTests the hypothesis that b_1 = 0 in the quantile regression model
X
X	y = X_0 b_0 + X_1 b_1 + u 
X.CS
Xrrs.test(x0, x1, y, v, score="wilcoxon")
X.RA
X.AG x0
Xmatrix of maintained regressors, a column of ones is appended automatically
X.AG x1
Xmatrix of regressors under test
X.OA
X.AG y
Xresponse variable may be omitted if v is provided
X.AG v
Xregression quantile structure from rq(x0,y)
X.AG score
Xscore function for test (see ranks())
X.RT
X.RC sn
XTest statistic is asymptotically Chi-squared with rank(X1) degrees of freedom.
X.RC rank
Xvector of ranks
X.SE
X.DT
X.SH REFERENCES
X[1] Gutenbrunner, C., J. Jureckova,  Koenker, R. and  Portnoy, S.(1993)
X"Tests of Linear Hypotheses  based on Regression Rank Scores",
XJournal of Nonparametric Statistics, (2), 307-331.
X
X[2] Koenker, R.W. and d'Orey (1994).  "Remark on Alg. AS 229: Computing Dual
XRegression Quantiles and Regression Rank Scores", Applied Statistics, 43, 410-414.
X
X.SA
Xrq, ranks
X.EX
Xrrs.test(stack.x[,1:2],stack.x[,3],stack.loss)
X.KW regression quantiles, ranks, regresion rankscores
X.WR
SHAR_EOF
$TOUCH -am 0517200595 rrs.test.d &&
chmod 0644 rrs.test.d ||
echo "restore of rrs.test.d failed"
set `wc -c rrs.test.d`;Wc_c=$1
if test "$Wc_c" != "1126"; then
	echo original size 1126, current size $Wc_c
fi
# ============= trq.d ==============
echo "x - extracting trq.d (Text)"
sed 's/^X//' << 'SHAR_EOF' > trq.d &&
X.BG
X.FN trq
X.TL
XFunction to compute analogues of the trimmed mean 
Xfor the linear regression model.
X.DN
XThe function returns 
Xa regression trimmed mean and some associated test statistics.
XThe proportion a1 is trimmed from the lower tail and a2 from the upper tail.
XIf a1+a2=1 then a result is returned for the a1 quantile.
XIf a1+a2<1 two methods of trimming are possible described below as
X"primal" and "dual". The function "trq.print" may be used to print results in the style of ls.print.
X.CS
Xtrq(x, y, a1=0.1, a2,  int=T, z,  method="primal", tol=1e-4)
X.RA
X.AG x
Xvector or matrix of explanatory variables.  If  a  matrix,
Xeach  column represents a variable and each row represents
Xan observation (or case).  This should not contain  column
Xof  1s unless the argument intercept is FALSE.  The number
Xof rows of x should equal the number of elemants of  y,  and
Xthere  should  be fewer columns than rows.  Missing values
Xare not  allowed.
X.AG y
Xreponse vector with as many observations as the number of rows of x.  
XMissing value are not allowed.
X.OA
X.AG a1
Xthe lower trimming proportion; defaults to .1 if missing.
X.AG a2
Xthe upper trimming proportion; defaults to a1 if missing.
X.AG int
Xflag for intercept; if TRUE, an intercept term is included in regrssion model. 
XThe default includes an intercept term.
X.AG z
Xstructure returned by the function 'rq' with t <0 or >1. If missing, the function rq(x,y,int=int) is automatically called to generate this argument.
XIf several calls to trq are anticipated for the same data this avoids
Xrecomputing the rq solution for each call.
X.AG method
Xmethod to be used for the trimming. 
XIf the choice is "primal", as is the default, a trimmed mean 
Xof the primal regression quantiles  is computed based on the sol array 
Xin the 'rq' structure. 
XIf the method is "dual", a weighted least-squares fit is done 
Xusing the dual solution in the 'rq' structure to construct weights.
XThe former method is discussed in detail in Koenker and Potnoy(1987)
Xthe latter in Ruppert and Carroll(1980) and Gutenbrunner and Jureckova(1991).
X.AG tol
XTolerance parameter for rq computions
X.RT
X.RC coef
Xestimated coeficient vector
X.RC resid
Xresiduals from the fit.
X.RC cov
Xthe estimated covariance matrix for the coeficient vector. 
X.RC v
Xthe scaling factor of the covariance matrix under iid error assumption:
Xcov=v*(x'x)^(-1).
X.RC wt
Xthe weights used in the least squares computation,  Returned only when
Xmethod="dual".
X.RC d
Xthe bandwidth used to compute the sparsity function. 
XReturned only when a1+a2=1.
X.EX
Xz_rq(x,y)  #z gets the full regression quantile structure
Xtrq(x,y,.05,z=z)  #5% symmetric primal trimming 
Xtrq(x,y,.01,.03,method="dual")  #1% lower and 3% upper trimmed least-
X			    #squares fit. 
Xtrq.print(trq(x,y)) #prints trq results in the style of ls.print.
X.KW regression quantiles, robust regression, trimmed mean
X.SH METHOD
Xdetails of the methods may be found in Koenker and Portnoy(1987) for
Xthe case of primal trimming and in Gutenbrunner and Jureckova(1991) for
Xdual trimming.
XOn the estimation of the covariance matrix for individual quantiles,
Xsee Koenker(1987) and the discussion in Hendricks and Koenker(1991).
XThe estimation of the covariance matrix under  non-iid
Xconditions is an open research problem.  
X.SH REFERENCE
XBassett, G., and Koenker, R. (1982), "An Empirical Quantile Function 
Xfor Linear Models With iid Errors," 
X.ul
XJournal of the American Statistical Association,
X77, 407-415.
X.PP
XKoenker, R.W. (1987), "A Comparison of Asymptotic Methods of Testing
Xbased on L1 Estimation," in Y. Dodge (ed.) 
X.ul
XStatistical Data Analysis Based on the L1 norm and Related Methods,
XNew York:  North-Holland.
X.PP
XKoenker, R. W., and Bassett, G.W (1978), "Regression Quantiles",
X.ul
XEconometrica,
X46, 33-50.
X.PP
XKoenker, R., and Portnoy, S. (1987), "L-Estimation for Linear Models",
X.ul
XJournal of the American Statistical Association,
X82, 851-857.
X.PP
XRuppert, D. and Carroll, R.J. (1980), "Trimmed Least Squares Estimation
Xin the Linear Model", 
X.ul
XJournal of the American Statistical Association, 75, 828-838.
X.SH SEE ALSO
Xrq and qrq for further details.
X.WR
SHAR_EOF
$TOUCH -am 0517200595 trq.d &&
chmod 0644 trq.d ||
echo "restore of trq.d failed"
set `wc -c trq.d`;Wc_c=$1
if test "$Wc_c" != "4113"; then
	echo original size 4113, current size $Wc_c
fi
# ============= trq.print.d ==============
echo "x - extracting trq.print.d (Text)"
sed 's/^X//' << 'SHAR_EOF' > trq.print.d &&
X.BG
X.FN trq.print
X.TL
XPrint a Trimmed Regression Quantile Summary
X.DN
XPrints out a summary of a trimmed quantile regression (using trq) including the standard error of the residuals, the overall F-statistic and t-statistics and standard errors for each coefficient.
X.CS
Xtrq.print(trq.out, digits=4)
X.RA
X.AG trq.out
Xa list like the output from trq.
X.OA
X.AG digits
Xthe number of significant digits that should be printed.
X.RT
Xan invisible list with the following components:
X.RC summary
Xa vector containig the winsorized standard error of regression, 
Xthe number of observations, the overall F-statistic for the regression, 
Xthe degrees of freedom and the p-value for the F-statistic. 
XWhen a1+a2=1, residual winsorized standard
Xerror is the the square root of a Siddiqui-type estimate of the asymtotic
Xvariance of the a1-quantile.
X.RC coef.table
Xa matrix with columns containing the regrssion coefficients, their standard error,the t-statistic for testing if the coefficient os zero and the two sided p-value for the t statistic.
X.SE
Xa summary of the regression (like the returned value) is printed out.
X.SA
Xtrq, lsfit, and ls.print for further reference.
X.EX
Xtrq.print(trq(x,y))
X.KW ~keyword
X.WR
SHAR_EOF
$TOUCH -am 0517200595 trq.print.d &&
chmod 0644 trq.print.d ||
echo "restore of trq.print.d failed"
set `wc -c trq.print.d`;Wc_c=$1
if test "$Wc_c" != "1196"; then
	echo original size 1196, current size $Wc_c
fi
exit 0
